---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Where is the mains water shutoff on a typical Hobart house?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "On most Hobart blocks the TasWater meter sits in a concrete pit near the front boundary, with the shutoff valve directly upstream of it. Older Battery Point and West Hobart cottages sometimes have the meter at the side gate instead. Inside the house there is usually a second shutoff at the wet-area wall behind the laundry tub or kitchen sink."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I take photos before I clean up?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — wide shots of the room, close-ups of the failed fitting, and a photo of the water level against a known object like a skirting board. Insurance assessors strongly prefer photos taken before mop-up. Keep the failed pipe or fitting in a plastic bag for the assessor."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is freeze damage common in Hobart?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Less than the highlands, but yes — copper feeds running through unheated under-floor spaces in West Hobart, North Hobart and parts of Glenorchy do split during cold snaps, particularly when a southerly front drops temperatures below freezing for several consecutive nights. The damage often shows up on the first warm day, not during the cold itself."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Who pays — TasWater or me?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The split is at the meter. Anything upstream of the meter is TasWater's responsibility; anything downstream, including the rising main into the house, is yours and your insurer's. If you suspect the leak is in the street side, ring TasWater's faults line first."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What about the heater if the burst is near the gas line?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If water is pooling near a gas appliance or gas pipework, isolate gas at the meter as well as water at the mains. Do not relight pilot lights until a Class A gasfitter has tested the connection — AS/NZS 5601.1 makes that a mandatory leak test before any reignition."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Burst Pipe Response in Hobart — Minutes-to-Shutoff & Flood Mitigation | Hobart Gas Heater Service"
  description="A burst pipe in a Hobart home: where the TasWater shutoff is, what to do in the first ten minutes, what to photograph for the insurance assessor, and when to ring a plumber vs the water authority."
  canonical="https://hobartgasheaterservice.com.au/burst-pipe-response-hobart/"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <main>
    <section class="hero">
      <h1>Burst pipe response in Hobart — minutes-to-shutoff and flood mitigation</h1>
      <p class="lede">You have ten minutes from the moment the pipe lets go to when the soaked carpet underlay starts wicking water into the wall plaster. Here is the playbook we run every winter on Hobart homes, written so you can act before we even leave the depot.</p>
      <p>Emergency line: <a href="tel:+61485939966">+61 485 939 966</a>. We answer at any hour.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The first ten minutes — what you do before we arrive</h2>
      <p>The single most useful skill any Hobart homeowner can have is knowing where the water comes into the house, and being able to turn it off in the dark. If you have not located the mains shutoff before, take five minutes this weekend to find it, label it, and try turning it through one full rotation. The valve will be stiffer than you expect — older quarter-turn handles can seize after a decade untouched, and you do not want to discover that at three in the morning.</p>
      <p>The first sixty seconds matter more than anything else that happens. Get the mains off. If the burst is on a hot line you will also need to isolate the gas heater so the unit does not run dry — a continuous-flow gas water heater that fires with no water in the heat exchanger is an expensive way to learn a lesson. Most Rinnai, Bosch and Rheem units have a gas isolation tap directly below the unit on the wall.</p>
      <h3>The minute-by-minute</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>0 to 1 min:</strong> Mains off at the boundary meter or the in-house isolation. Gas off at the heater if the leak is on a hot line.</li>
        <li><strong>1 to 3 min:</strong> Towels, sheets, anything absorbent at the boundary of the wet area. Lift the edges of rugs. Move books, laptops and power boards onto a table — water on a powerboard is the second emergency you do not want.</li>
        <li><strong>3 to 6 min:</strong> Photos. Wide shot of the room, close on the failed component, water-level shot against a skirting board for the assessor.</li>
        <li><strong>6 to 10 min:</strong> Ring us. Open windows if you have any concern about a gas appliance nearby. Start moving furniture off wet carpet — the underlay is the part that holds the water and rots the floor.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Where Hobart pipes tend to fail</h2>
      <p>Hobart has a particular failure profile that differs from mainland cities. The mid-century housing stock in West Hobart, North Hobart, New Town and the older parts of Sandy Bay was largely plumbed in copper, often with brazed joints in subfloor spaces that the original installer assumed would never see freezing temperatures. They do, intermittently, on the worst three or four nights of winter when a southerly buster sits over the city for forty-eight hours. The split itself often happens silently overnight; the leak only becomes obvious when the ice plug melts on the first sunny afternoon.</p>
      <p>Newer estates in Kingston, Bellerive and Lindisfarne are mostly Pex (cross-linked polyethylene), which handles freeze cycles much better but has its own failure mode at brass crimp fittings, particularly where they pass through wall plates and pick up movement loads. Battery Point's heritage cottages are a mixed bag — anything that has been renovated in the last decade should be reasonably modern, but unrenovated original work can still surface galvanised steel pipework that is well past its design life.</p>
      <h3>Cold-snap preparation</h3>
      <p>If a frost is forecast and you have any exposed copper under the house, run a low trickle from the most distant tap overnight. Lag exposed pipework with foam sleeves from the hardware store. If you are leaving the house empty for the Hobart winter — a holiday-home pattern for many Sandy Bay and Battery Point owners — drain the system down at the heater isolation and shut the mains. The cost of a winterise visit from us is a small fraction of the cost of returning to a flooded house in August.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Insurance, paperwork and what we provide</h2>
      <p>The assessor will want three things from us: a written scope of the repair, the failed component if we can preserve it, and confirmation that the new work complies with AS/NZS 3500 plumbing standards. For any work on the gas side of the house, a Certificate of Compliance through the Tasmanian Consumer Building and Occupational Services portal is mandatory and is provided as part of the job, not as a separate charge. Keep these documents — they matter at conveyancing.</p>
      <p>If the burst is on the street side of the meter, the right phone call is TasWater first. They are responsible for everything upstream of the meter. Some property owners do not realise that a leak under the front lawn might not be their problem at all — we will help you work out where the responsibility line sits before any chargeable work begins.</p>
      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <h3>Where is the mains water shutoff on a typical Hobart house?</h3>
      <p>On most Hobart blocks the TasWater meter sits in a concrete pit near the front boundary, with the shutoff valve directly upstream of it. Older Battery Point and West Hobart cottages sometimes have the meter at the side gate instead. Inside the house there is usually a second shutoff at the wet-area wall behind the laundry tub or kitchen sink.</p>
      <h3>Should I take photos before I clean up?</h3>
      <p>Yes — wide shots of the room, close-ups of the failed fitting, and a photo of the water level against a known object like a skirting board. Insurance assessors strongly prefer photos taken before mop-up. Keep the failed pipe or fitting in a plastic bag for the assessor.</p>
      <h3>Is freeze damage common in Hobart?</h3>
      <p>Less than the highlands, but yes — copper feeds running through unheated under-floor spaces in West Hobart, North Hobart and parts of Glenorchy do split during cold snaps, particularly when a southerly front drops temperatures below freezing for several consecutive nights.</p>
      <h3>Who pays — TasWater or me?</h3>
      <p>The split is at the meter. Anything upstream of the meter is TasWater's responsibility; anything downstream, including the rising main into the house, is yours and your insurer's.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="cta">
      <h2>Ring us — and find your shutoff before you need to</h2>
      <p>If a pipe has gone now, ring <a href="tel:+61485939966">+61 485 939 966</a> while you walk to the meter. If everything is dry today, do the five-minute test on your shutoff valve this weekend — that one habit has saved more Hobart living rooms than any other piece of advice we give. Quotes and questions to <a href="mailto:quotes@hobartgasheaterservice.com.au">quotes@hobartgasheaterservice.com.au</a>.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
